{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492836"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:46:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:46:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1167"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1167"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.05,0.28,0.54,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1167"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32737"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1167"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1167"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18240"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"100"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8087"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8122"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32737","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/32737"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 68-year-old man is admitted for a total hip arthroplasty. This is being done for degenerative disease. His medical history is unremarkable and he is not on any medications. Arrangements will be made to minimise his risk of post-operative venous thromboembolic complications. Apart from the use of graded compression stocking and sequential compression device (SCD), other measures must be considered.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aspirin for 2 weeks after discharge","Clopidogrel for 4 weeks after discharge","Rivaroxaban for 2 weeks after discharge","Enoxaparin for 4 weeks after discharge","Warfarin for 3 months after discharge"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAll patients undergoing hip and knee arthroplasty with a routine risk of venous thromboembolism (VTE) should be offered SCDs unless otherwise contraindicated. They should also be offered pharmacological prophylaxis, which can be either aspirin, warfarin, low molecular weight heparin (LMWH), or a direct-acting oral anticoagulant (DOAC) for a duration of 3 to 6 weeks after joint arthroplasty. The choice of VTE prophylaxis should be made based on the type of surgery and patient risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs this patient has no VTE risk factors or bleeding risk factors they fall under the category of routine risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin \u003C/strong\u003Ecan be given at 150mg daily for VTE prophylaxis in patients undergoing hip arthroplasty but the duration of 2 weeks is insufficient, thus this answer is incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClopidogrel \u003C/strong\u003Eis not indicated for VTE prophylaxis and is incorrect. It is typically ceased at 7 days before surgery and recommenced post-operatively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERivaroxaban\u003C/strong\u003E is a DOAC, which can be given at 10mg daily for 2 weeks for VTE prophylaxis in a total knee arthroplasty, but is required for 28-35 days for total hip arthroplasty. This patient is receiving a total hip arthroplasty, thus the duration of 2 weeks is insufficient and this answer is incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnoxaparin \u003C/strong\u003Eis LMWH and can be given at 40mg daily for 28-35 days for VTE prophylaxis for total hip arthroplasty. Therefore, this is the correct answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin \u003C/strong\u003Emay be appropriate in certain circumstances but this choice and duration of 3 months is inappropriate for this patient who is otherwise well and was not previously on warfarin.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["VTE prophylaxis should be for 3 to 6 weeks after joint replacement"],"references":["Arthroplasty Society of Australia. Arthroplasty Society of Australia Guidelines for VTE Prophlyaxis for Hip and Knee Arthroplasty. 2018 Jan;","Falck-Ytter Y, Francis CW, Johanson NA, et al. Prevention of VTE in Orthopedic Surgery Patients. Chest 2012; 141:78S\u2013e325S"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18240"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1167"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18240","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/18240"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-02-19T09:35:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-02-19T09:35:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1167"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32737"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes"